1.2 The Causal Trinity: Three Languages for One Idea
The same causal question — what happens when we set \(T = t\)? — can be expressed in three distinct but equivalent languages. Collectively, we call these the causal trinity: the structural equation model (SEM), the directed acyclic graph (DAG) with graph surgery, and the potential outcomes framework. Each member of the trinity illuminates a different facet of the same underlying idea, and fluency in all three is essential for modern causal reasoning. ?fig-trinity depicts their relationships.
