1.4.5 The IV DAG Versus the Mediation DAG
The IV DAG introduced above looks, at first glance, structurally similar to the mediation DAG that will appear in Chapter 8. The similarity is superficial; the conceptual difference is fundamental. Confusing the two is one of the most common errors in applied causal inference.
?fig-iv-vs-med places the two DAGs side by side.
#| label: fig-iv-vs-med
#| fig-cap: "The IV DAG (a) and the mediation DAG (b) both involve a three-node chain, but they are structurally and conceptually distinct. In (a), the instrument $Z$ is pre-treatment and exogenous: it satisfies $Z \\indep U$ and has no direct path to $Y$ (exclusion restriction). In (b), the mediator $M$ is post-treatment and endogenous: it is caused by $T$ and transmits part of $T$'s effect to $Y$."
